{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533090"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:32:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14751"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14751"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.02,0.27,0.24,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"5570"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18218"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after being found unconscious by her housemate. Empty packets of diazepam and amitriptyline were found nearby. The exact time and dose of ingestion is unknown. She has a history of depression and anxiety. On examination, she appears drowsy with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 9 (E2 V2 M5). Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 6/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her pupils are 4 mm and reactive. ECG shows sinus tachycardia with a QRS duration of 100ms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intubation and ventilation","Gastric lavage","Administer flumazenil","Administer sodium bicarbonate","Administer activated charcoal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with decreased consciousness and respiratory depression due to mixed overdose of benzodiazepines and tricyclic antidepressants. The priority in managing any overdose is ensuring airway protection and adequate ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step given the low Glasgow Coma Scale score and respiratory depression (respiratory rate 6/min with hypoxia). This will secure the airway and prevent aspiration while allowing for supportive care during the recovery period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlumazenil\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in mixed overdoses involving tricyclic antidepressants as it may precipitate seizures by antagonising the anticonvulsant effect of benzodiazepines. This could be particularly dangerous in tricyclic overdose where the seizure threshold is already lowered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is only useful within one hour of ingestion and should only be given if the airway is protected. In this case, the time of ingestion is unknown and the patient\u0027s airway is compromised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for treating QRS prolongation in tricyclic overdose, but as the QRS duration is normal in this case, it is not currently needed. The patient should continue to be monitored for development of conduction abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely indicated in modern toxicology as it carries significant risks and has limited benefits. It is contraindicated in this case due to the decreased level of consciousness and unprotected airway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter securing the airway, ongoing management would include cardiac monitoring (due to risk of arrhythmias from tricyclic toxicity), and supportive care until the drugs are metabolised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Flumazenil should be avoided in mixed overdoses involving tricyclic antidepressants due to risk of seizures.","Initial management of mixed overdoses focuses on airway protection and supportive care.","Activated charcoal is only indicated within one hour of ingestion if the airway is protected."],"references":["An H, Godwin J. Flumazenil in benzodiazepine overdose. CMAJ. 2016 Dec 6;188(17-18):E537. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.160357. Epub 2016 Nov 14. PMID: 27920113; PMCID: PMC5135539.","Kang M, Galuska MA, Ghassemzadeh S. Benzodiazepine Toxicity. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482238/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14751"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T16:01:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T16:02:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com